export const batch164 = {
  'seven-kinds-of-people-you-find-in-bookshops.json': {
    base: { id: 'seven-kinds-of-people-you-find-in-bookshops', title: 'Seven Kinds of People You Find in Bookshops', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781682868732 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Inside the bookstore world',
        text: "Shaun Bythell runs the largest second-hand bookshop in Scotland, and his love for the trade is matched by his worry about where it is heading. After more than twenty years behind the counter, he started sorting his customers into a Linnaean-style system with Latin names. He calls them Peritus, Familia Juvenis, Homo qui maleficas amat, Homo qui desidet, Senex cum barba, Viator non tacitus, and Parentum historiae studiosus.\n\nA bookshop only works when the seller learns what each customer wants and adapts to them.\n\nBythell also added a bonus group for the Staff and their many types, and he described the dream customer that every seller would love to meet.\n\nRead on and you will meet the sly Antiquarian, the shy Erotica Browser, the clueless Student Hugo, the eager Sci-Fi Fan, the hungry Railway Collector, and the rare Perfect Customer."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: The self-appointed expert',
        text: "The Expert has no real audience, yet they speak as if a crowd waits for their wisdom. They reach for the longest, most complex word available when a short one would do, mostly to feel clever.\n\nFive species fall under this genus.\n\nFirst, the Specialist. A bookshop covers so many subjects that no seller can know them all, and Specialists love that gap. They walk in to lecture the seller about their narrow field and enjoy the fact that the seller cannot argue back. Some are polite enough to notice that their passion is not universal, but they still take pride in being different.\n\nSecond, the Bore. The Bore shares an opinion on every topic, and sometimes jumps into other customers' conversations with rude rants. They call themselves a polymath. The best move is to avoid them or stay silent, because any small sign of interest triggers an endless speech on the most random subjects.\n\nThird, the Helpful Person. Some experts are a gift. They drop a few sharp facts into a short chat and leave the seller wanting more. Their tidbits arm the seller with the knowledge they need to sound confident in front of the next customer.\n\nFourth, the Antiquarian Book Collector. They care about the book as a physical thing, not for the words inside. Their skill is spotting the small details that set one edition apart from another, and they always know the mistakes that mark a particular printing. They will grumble about prices and swear they saw the same copy cheaper somewhere else.\n\nFifth, the Home Mechanic. The Home Mechanic thinks every book should be about cars. They hunt for manuals and even pick up copies for friends, then use what they read to fix real problems.\n\nOf the five, the Specialist and the Bore are the two you wish would leave."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: The young family',
        text: "Young families bring their kids into the shop and quietly undo all the work the seller did to keep the place tidy. The genus has four species worth knowing.\n\nThe first is the Exhausted Parents. They are usually a couple with a large family, often with at least one baby. Their real reason for visiting is to tire the children out so they can finally get some quiet.\n\nThe second is the Abandoned Child. It is common to see a father walk in with his child, hand them a picture book, and steer them toward the kids' corner. Then he slips toward the door and tells the seller he will be right back. The promised minute usually stretches into much more, and the return comes with weak excuses and fake apologies.\n\nThe third is the Aspirational Parents. They want their children to read well, so they push books on them that the kids do not care about. This pressure tends to make the children unhappy and slows their reading growth. Children who pick their own books tend to read more and enjoy it more.\n\nThe fourth is the Book-loving Children. These young readers love books and often drag a reluctant parent to the shop with them.\n\nWhen you design the children's section, keep adults in mind, because many of them come back for the books they loved as kids."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: Occultist',
        text: "The Occultist is sure that the unbelievable is real, and that certainty gives them a strange sense of being above everyone else. They usually browse alone, and their social skills and personal hygiene are not always great.\n\nThere are five types in this genus.\n\nThe first is the Dark Artist. Dressed in black, often carrying extra weight, and drawn to the works of Aleister Crowley, they tend to be men who see occult book sellers as unbelievers. They treat the sale of mystical books as a betrayal of the deep secrets they follow, and the group also includes some Wiccans.\n\nThe second is the Conspiracy Theorist. This quiet group asks about strange subjects, from the events of September 11 to the Kennedy assassination to antisemitic plots. They blend in at first, so they are easy to miss. When they come in to sell books, the bags usually hold titles on UFOs, voodoo, and poltergeists that few others want. Respect their interests, because they are loyal to unusual theories.\n\nThe third is the Tarot Reader. They gaze into crystal balls to predict the future, and their wider practice can include dream reading, Celtic mythology, horoscopes, palm reading, spiritual healing, and rune casting. They tend to wear loose clothes covered in pet hair and leave the smell of old incense behind them. Convinced that people will pay for their gifts, they often buy self-help books to set up a small business.\n\nThe fourth is the Ghost Hunter. Most people say they believe in ghosts, but very few bookshop customers actually hunt for ghost books. The few who do leave a strong, sometimes annoying, impression.\n\nThe fifth is the Craft Enthusiast. Their look is so close to the Tarot Reader that the two are easy to confuse. Mostly women, they drift through the shop with a mysterious air, never quite sure what they want, and they often leave without buying anything useful.\n\nFor context, a 2021 Ipsos poll found that 36 percent of Americans believe in ghosts and 39 percent believe in UFOs."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: Loiterer',
        text: "The Loiterer shows up for no clear reason and hovers in a way that feels slightly off. They give off the feeling that they are about to ask a question, so the seller stays close. When they finally speak, the question is never about books. They want the time, a good lunch place, or the nearest bus stop.\n\nLoiterers make the air feel heavier than it is.\n\nThere are four species in this genus.\n\nThe first is the Erotica Browser. They are usually older men, dressed to avoid notice in long coats and hats, sometimes with dark glasses. They try to look casual as they slide adult books into other sections, like the railway shelves, and they swap dust jackets without putting them back. Giggling teenagers also fall into this group, wandering the aisles and laughing at the racier titles until they hear a parent and scatter. A sharp contrast is the young adult woman who reads the same shelves calmly, with mixed feelings and no rush.\n\nThe second is the Loiterer without Intent. They come in to kill time while waiting on something nearby, like a takeout order or a car wash. They have no plan to buy, and they flip through pages just to fill the wait.\n\nThe third is the Bored Spouse. They find books dull and look for a soft corner to settle in, often playing games on their phone while their partner browses. Crossed arms, loud sighs, and a constant watch check are the usual signs that they have had enough.\n\nThe fourth is the Self-published Author. Self-publishing has opened the door to everyone from talented writers to weaker ones. Without a big publisher behind them, these authors often approach sellers and try to convince them to stock their books."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: Bearded pensioner',
        text: "Most members of this genus tour the country in a motorhome or caravan, complain about everything, and never buy a thing. They may park their vehicle right in front of the shop and never worry that they are blocking the view.\n\nThere are four species in this genus.\n\nThe first is the Lycra-clad. Usually a couple, they walk straight to the map section, spread out every chart to plan their week, and end up blocking a doorway. They refold the maps wrong and leave without a word to the staff.\n\nThe second is the Pantalons Rouges. Mostly older and either large or tall and thin, they are not browsers. They know what they want and walk right to it with a steady focus. Price is not a concern.\n\nThe third is the Downsizers. They are only seen in second-hand shops. Usually pensioners, they try to convince the seller that the book they want to sell is worth a fortune. In most cases, they are moving to a smaller home and want to let go of a few things. Be kind to them, because the items they bring often mean a lot.\n\nThe fourth is the Miser. Misers are stingy people who cannot accept that prices rise. Some get loud and accuse the seller of overcharging."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: The Not-So-Silent Traveler',
        text: "The Silent Traveler was the pen name of Chang Yee, a writer who looked at everyday life with curious wonder. His skill came from seeing things as an outsider without all the local context. By watching quietly, he caught the beauty in the ordinary and shared it with his readers in a fresh way.\n\nThis genus has five species.\n\nThe first is the Whistler. They are not there to buy. They wander the shop and whistle, and the tune is rarely musical. The stares do not make them stop.\n\nThe second is the Sniffer. They have a cold and refuse to blow their nose, so they sniff loudly as they wander the shelves and pick up books.\n\nThe third is the Hummer. Where the Whistler makes random noise, the Hummer tries to stay close to a real tune. When both the Whistler and the Hummer visit the same shop on the same day, the noise is hard to bear.\n\nThe fourth is the Farter. Whether the result is silent or loud, they usually find a quiet corner for the deed, though sometimes the counter is the spot they choose. Spotting them in time is not always easy.\n\nThe fifth is the Tutter. They are easy to spot by the constant head shake and the unhappy sounds they make. Nothing the seller does seems good enough, and the only thing they enjoy is finding fault.\n\nThe Not-So-Silent Traveler does not watch quietly. They like attention, on purpose or not."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: Family Historian',
        text: "Bythell believes that tracing a family line is not as special as people think, since we all share the same distant roots.\n\nHe has also said that people who study their family tree are usually trying to prove a small point.\n\nMany Americans with roots in rural Scotland still feel a strong bond to their clan. They walk into bookshops hoping to find books about their family, and they often expect there to be far more books on their particular line than there really are. Bythell sees this as a mostly American habit, although a strong interest in family roots can show up in other countries, including Australia and New Zealand.\n\nTracing a family line through the generations can give a person a stronger sense of identity."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: Staff',
        text: "The staff is the bridge between the books on the shelves and the people who come in to buy them. They are the face of the shop, and they keep the whole thing running.\n\nThere are five types of staff.\n\nThe first is Student Hugo. He is usually a relative of the owner, comes from a wealthy family, and is in the shop because a bored parent or a playful godparent thought a summer behind the counter would do him good. Hugo is not strong in the role, struggles to get along with other staff, and rarely helps customers well.\n\nThe second is Student Mary. Like Hugo, she works through a university break, but her reasons are different. She needs the money and has a love of art, which makes her more able to help. She still fights with self-doubt, even though she is useful.\n\nThe third is the Hipster. The Hipster is the opposite of Mary. They are in the shop to be seen, not to help. They give off a distant air, lost in their own thoughts or a book, often stroking their beard. When a customer interrupts, their response ranges from unhelpful to annoyed.\n\nThe fourth is the Second-hand Bookseller. Usually self-employed, they sell books because they have to, not because they chose to. They prefer paper over digital, and years at the counter have given them a visible dislike for customers. They have been in the trade so long that they cannot remember exactly how they started.\n\nThe fifth is the Manager. Well dressed, on time, and full of energy, the Manager believes the customer is always right. They are rare in second-hand shops and far more common in stores that sell new books, which sets them apart from the earlier three types.\n\nIf you really need help in the shop, look for a Manager or a Student Mary."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genus: Perfect customer',
        text: "The customers a bookshop owner dreams about love being surrounded by second-hand books, and they value the worlds that clever authors have built. For them, reading is a way to step away from the everyday. This kind of customer is rare now, because the rise of e-books means fewer people care about paper copies.\n\nAny edition can turn out to be a rare treasure years later, so it pays to treat books with care.\n\nOne type of perfect customer is the fiction collector, who is always on the hunt for rare editions and never haggles. Another is the railway collector, who treats the seller like royalty and reads anything about trains. A third is the reading enthusiast who walks in without a title in mind but leaves with a book. They are open to suggestions, and they happily pay the asking price without a fight. The last is the Sci-Fi Fan, who never comes alone. They know the other fans and spread the word about new collections. They are rarely disappointed, as long as the shop stocks their favorite authors.\n\nGeorge R.R. Martin once said that a reader lives a thousand lives before they die, while the person who never reads only lives one."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Booksellers deal with every kind of customer each day, from the rude to the charming. Beyond the money from sales, the small interactions with each quirky buyer are what make the job interesting. No matter how harsh a customer seems on the surface, there is usually a kind person underneath.\n\nThe book trade is more than a simple buyer and seller. Knowing the different types of customers forces the seller to step into other roles at different times, including detective, psychologist, agent, or scholar. Whichever role is needed, it always pulls the seller a little further from the basic job.\n\nWhen sorting book lovers into types, remember that any system only captures broad traits. People are far more complex, and each one carries a mix of qualities that no label can fully cover.\n\nTry this. From the broad list of customers and staff in a bookshop, find the type you fit into. Think about how you could be a better customer or a better staff member."
      }
    ]
  },

  'she-said.json': {
    base: { id: 'she-said', title: 'She Said', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781682975396 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Women began to speak up about their experiences, and this changed everything',
        text: "Many things look impossible until one brave person tries. Breaking the Harvey Weinstein story was one of them. Few people thought that the hidden acts of such a powerful Hollywood producer would ever be exposed to the world.\n\nJodi Kantor has written that harassers were often treated as cheeky bad boys, and even cheered on.\n\nMost people brushed off his behavior as a rich man's habit and paid it no real attention, especially since he bragged about his feminist credentials in public. He gave loans to women's groups and joined marches against assault. Earlier investigations into his conduct found nothing solid, and many reporters tried without ever landing a story.\n\nEveryone has the right to live and work without fear of being harmed by another person.\n\nThe courage that many victims of sexual abuse now show comes from the victory won by the women whose stories fill this summary. This piece shows that even the most powerful people who break the law can be held to account. It also gives hope in situations that feel hopeless. Read on to learn how eighty-seven women chose to break the silence around sexual harassment by sharing their stories."
      },
      {
        title: 'It all began with Rose McGowan\'s decision to tell her story',
        text: "Rumors about Harvey Weinstein and his power over women had been swirling for years. At first, Rose McGowan refused to talk to a reporter after accusing him of rape. She did share social media posts that called out sexist movie roles and views. The claims were hard to swallow at first, since Weinstein had launched the careers of many young women, including Jennifer Lawrence, Michelle Williams, and Gwyneth Paltrow, along with male stars like Matt Damon. He had also helped with Hillary Clinton fundraisers, and Malia Obama had interned with him.\n\nIt is hard to believe abuse claims when the accused is a respected figure.\n\nMcGowan eventually told her full story. In 1997, she met Weinstein at the Sundance Film Festival to talk about roles, and he pushed her into a bathroom, stripped her, and forced his face between her legs. She got away by faking an orgasm. She received a hundred thousand dollar settlement, which she gave to a rape crisis center. The experience led her to see Hollywood as a system that used young women and threw them away.\n\nBefore the Times could publish, they had to give Weinstein a fair chance to respond, since there was no video and no witnesses. Rebecca Corbett, a long-time editor at the Times, helped Jodi Kantor see that more victims were out there. Jodi teamed up with Megan Twohey, who had covered Donald Trump's behavior toward women and had uncovered many cases of sexual crime. Megan had also seen how the police sometimes failed victims and how abusive doctors kept practicing. Jodi had started in 2013 looking into women's experiences at companies and other institutions, and she found many workers too afraid to speak up because they worried about losing their jobs.\n\nThe goal of the MeToo movement was to protect others from harm, not to rewrite the past.\n\nOne big reason victims came forward and joined the movement was that the reporters cared about shielding others from becoming victims."
      },
      {
        title: 'There is strength in numbers: the more women that spoke up, the more evidence was made available',
        text: "Gathering testimony from leading ladies was hard. They guarded their public image and put walls around anyone trying to reach them.\n\nJodi combed through pictures from Cannes in France, looking for emails and phone numbers attached to women who had worked on Weinstein's films. When she did track someone down, the chats stayed short and went nowhere.\n\nFear of professional ruin kept many from cooperating with the investigation.\n\nThe bulk of Weinstein's ex-staff either clammed up or tossed out scraps that could not stand on their own. With a handful of helpers, Jodi managed to reach other actresses who, only after making her promise secrecy, opened up about an industry built on exploitation. Two of them, Daryl Hannah and Judith Godreche, said they had been hurt, but were too frightened to go further.\n\nGwyneth Paltrow met Weinstein at the Toronto Film Festival in 1994, when she was twenty-two. He dangled two projects in front of her, she signed on with Miramax, and her relationship with Brad Pitt began. True to form, Weinstein then summoned her to a hotel meeting and suggested they exchange massages. She made an excuse, told Brad, and he confronted Weinstein and warned him off. Weinstein bristled and threatened her, terrified she would bring up the hotel scene years later. Paltrow avoided a scandal and kept quiet until she sat down with Jodi. Once she realized a strong enough case could end Weinstein, she agreed to help connect Jodi to other survivors.\n\nPaltrow decided to add her own account to the growing file of abuse stories.\n\nTwo additional women confirmed the same script, describing how Weinstein used business meetings as a cover for unwanted advances. Heavyweights like Angelina Jolie, Uma Thurman, and Salma Hayek each had their own tale of inappropriate conduct from him. Only Italian model Ambra Battilana Gutierrez had actually reported him to the police.\n\nPlenty of abuse survivors keep silent rather than live with the stigma that often follows speaking up.\n\nOnce the first accounts landed, fresh voices kept arriving. People who had been inside Weinstein's circle for years began describing how the routine worked. Their stories lined up with the earlier testimony and gave lawyers and reporters a much firmer foundation to build on."
      },
      {
        title: 'The more stories that were uncovered, the more courageous other victims became',
        text: "Megan kept digging through public records of Weinstein's behavior, which was hard because non-disclosure agreements destroyed the records and blocked anyone from sharing the names of complainants.\n\nNew harassment stories filled the news, and the pattern spread into other parts of the world. Men apologized, and victims were praised for their courage.\n\nOngoing exposure of sexual predators makes it safer for other victims to come forward.\n\nMany former staff refused to testify, share what they knew, or even return calls. Amy Israel did speak up. She described how Weinstein had harassed her at the Toronto Film Festival after inviting her to a business meeting in his hotel. In 1998, at the Venice Film Festival, she noticed two of Weinstein's assistants, Zelda Perkins and Rowena Chiu, looking scared while Weinstein pretended nothing was wrong. Both had signed agreements to keep quiet after he had harassed them at different times while they worked for him.\n\nEven with all of this, criminal proceedings could not move forward because there was not enough evidence.\n\nLaura Madden then came forward. In 1992, Weinstein had masturbated in front of her under the cover of a business meeting. She still spent six years working for him afterward.\n\nEven after the worst experiences, the women who worked for Weinstein wanted a chance to keep working, contributing, and succeeding."
      },
      {
        title: 'Sexual predators like Harvey Weinstein always want to keep up appearances; your job is not to keep silent',
        text: "Jodi and Megan were warned not to be rude to other journalists, to watch for desperate moves from Weinstein, and to be careful never to speak off the record.\n\nWeinstein had his lawyer, Lanny Davis, speak for him. Davis kept probing sources and claimed Weinstein was trying to fix the issues. After questions from Jodi and Megan, he admitted that a settlement had been made, then ran off saying he had to recheck his legal limits.\n\nWeinstein tried to kill the investigation by hiring The Black Cube to remove evidence and stop women from testifying.\n\nNobody wanted the world to know they had risen in their career by helping a predator. Jodi found help in Irwin Reiter, Weinstein's top lieutenant and vice president of Accounting and Financial Reporting. They met for several nights at a spot Reiter chose, and as he shared what he knew, Jodi realized Weinstein had committed new offenses.\n\nWealthy and well-known abusers often pay their victims to stay silent.\n\nReiter described how Emily Nestor, Weinstein's temporary receptionist, was pushed until she left the office, and how Weinstein's personal assistant was forced to get an erectile dysfunction drug for him and was even given a bonus for it.\n\nThere was also an investigation into how six hundred thousand dollars raised at a 2015 AIDS charity auction had ended up in investors' accounts.\n\nBob, Weinstein's brother, was awkward and volatile, and he soon fought with Harvey over money. Bob said Harvey had lied to him about the settlements, and Bob saw the behavior as a form of excess. Soon after a physical fight with his brother, Bob went through a divorce and a drinking problem, and he left the business to get help.\n\nThe Weinstein Company had no rules that could hold Harvey accountable for his actions.\n\nFor context, a 2008 survey found that most victims had met the abuser willingly. Of the 129 victims identified, those aged seventeen and younger had met the abuser face to face in 74 percent of cases, and 93 percent of those meetings included sexual contact.\n\nThe team also heard from a former driver who described late-night pickups and the strange routes Weinstein asked for. Combined with the assistant's account of running odd errands, the picture of a man who treated women as tools became harder to dismiss."
      },
      {
        title: 'Fear will keep you from speaking your truth, but once you do, you\'ll be free',
        text: "Lanny Davis, Weinstein's former lawyer, had told Megan roughly how many payments Weinstein had made. He thought it was between eight and twelve. That was not enough evidence. More proof was needed, and the fear of Weinstein's retaliation kept everyone worried about their reputation.\n\nJodi Kantor has said that there will never be a true end, and the point is for people to keep speaking up without fear.\n\nAt that point, it made sense to speak to Weinstein and his team and hear their side. With help from the Times' attorney and other editors, Jodi and Megan built a fireproof story.\n\nSexual offenders often blame the victim to excuse their acts.\n\nWeinstein refused to back down. He ordered his IT staff to delete a document with women's contact information, and he pressured employees to sign a written statement saying they had enjoyed their time at the company.\n\nRowena Chiu had never told her husband. The confidentiality clauses had trapped all three of them in strange positions, including a woman who could not share her own experience with her spouse."
      },
      {
        title: 'The threats from the opposition only made the reporters want to work even harder',
        text: "Word came back from the head of the Weinstein Company's California office. He was willing to share his side of the long-running story and to back up the dollar figure of the settlement. Weinstein's reply was sharp. He sent a message threatening to sue the Times. He tried to tear down the women's stories by lifting small photos and tidbits from their memoirs. He branded Laura Madden a liar. He demanded that Jodi and Megan hand over every document they had gathered.\n\nThe paper refused to back off. Reporters kept digging to put more victims on the record. In the end, Weinstein had to step away from the company and enter a treatment program at the board's request.\n\nThe story of Weinstein changed how the public expects men to treat women.\n\nFrom October 2017 onward, the newsroom was flooded with tips. American women had been carrying a heavy load. Many posted MeToo stories online, sharing what men had done to them. The change was powered by accountability, by the knowledge that sharing actually led to action.\n\nThe Times' reporting team on sexual harassment grew and started covering restaurant staff, dancers, factory workers, and many other fields.\n\nAfter the Weinstein case broke, the public took sexual crimes more seriously, largely because women chose to speak.\n\nLouis C. K. lost distribution for his next film after five women shared detailed accounts of his actions. In the same window, Christine Blasey Ford, who had been assaulted in college by Brett Kavanaugh, now a Supreme Court associate justice, stepped forward after years of trying to bury what had happened to her.\n\nRumors of Donald Trump's paid-off relationship with a porn star also drew headlines. The flood of claims against powerful men left many readers asking tough questions about the law and about the truth of what these women had said."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "What you have just read is built from the real experiences of real people. Each woman who shared her story of being harassed by Trump, Weinstein, Kavanaugh, or anyone else in this summary did it so that you, the reader, would feel brave enough to do the same, or to stand behind others who do.\n\nWeinstein leaned on his power and his long list of contacts to threaten everyone in the investigation, hoping they would back away. In the end, though, the head of his own company agreed to go on the record and speak up. Once that happened, more people stepped forward with their stories, and in some cases with proof, of what this serial abuser had done. The Weinstein case shows why so many molesters escape justice, especially when they have little reputation left to lose.\n\nFor a long time, the United States had a system that hushed claims of sexual harassment, and that system often shielded the harasser rather than stopping the harm. Women regularly signed documents giving up the right to discuss their own experiences. Abusers then moved on to new places and committed the same offenses all over again.\n\nEncouraged by the other women who shared a common abuser, they each found the strength to speak. Every woman was a messenger from a different world, the battleground Midwest, the strange niche of show business, or the charged arena of the Supreme Court. Those differences did not split the group. They sparked curiosity and pulled the women closer together.\n\nThe Weinstein story moved other women to share similar experiences, and that wave of honesty changed how employers and ordinary people treated the people around them.\n\nTry this. If you work in any organization, make sure it has clear, written rules against sexual harassment. Also, build a safe space at home where family and friends can speak out. If you lead a team, create a setting where staff can come forward with cases of abuse without fear of losing their job."
      }
    ]
  },

  'siblings-without-rivalry.json': {
    base: { id: 'siblings-without-rivalry', title: 'Siblings Without Rivalry', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781609152662 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Sibling rivalry happens even with the best parenting',
        text: "Stewart Stafford once summed up sibling rivalry with a sharp line. The oldest child is the golden one, the middle child is invisible, and the youngest is the loud one. That line captures the struggle of parents with more than one child. Can rivalry, competition, jealousy, and fighting be avoided?\n\nTension between kids in one family comes from many emotional factors. One child may feel less loved, may feel unsafe, or may be in constant competition with a sibling. These fights happen even when parents are doing their best.\n\nSibling rivalry does not define who your children are. It is okay to see your kids compete.\n\nAs a parent, your job is to understand why rivalry happens and to avoid blaming your own parenting for every fight. You also need real techniques for handling the tension and a strategy for raising confident kids.\n\nAre you ready to learn what it takes to shift your parenting? Keep reading."
      },
      {
        title: 'Don\'t repress negative feelings',
        text: "Kids often feel threatened by the mere presence of a sibling, and that can flare into outright rage. You see them scream at each other, and they come running to you to tattle. The urge to yell back or block out their feelings is strong, just to end the noise. But brushing past their anger teaches them to push it down, and that buried anger can show up as physical symptoms or emotional problems. If you want a real fix, accept their emotions and treat them with respect. Kids feel safer when someone is willing to sit with the hard feelings.\n\nTeaching your children to label their feelings helps them build healthy habits around emotion.\n\nLetting your kids voice their feelings about a sibling does not mean you agree with them. It does mean you can stop the hurtful behavior and show them a better way to express anger. Let them know they can show displeasure without causing damage. Faber and Mazlish give a clear example of how to handle this.\n\nInstead of saying something like, that is a terrible thing to do to the baby, she only touched your toys, show your child a better way by saying, no fighting. Tell your brother or sister how angry you are with words, not fists.\n\nThe second statement tells your child what to do when angry, while the first only teaches them that anger itself is bad. The goal is to give kids healthy ways to cope with frustration. Patience matters, and you have to model the behavior you want to see.\n\nAdele Faber and Elaine Mazlish have said that we let children express all their feelings, we do not let them hurt each other, and our job is to show them how to express anger without damage."
      },
      {
        title: 'Constant comparison increases anxiety',
        text: "One of the easiest ways parents stir up rivalry is by holding their kids up against each other. You hear lines like, your sister is so responsible, you would never see her room a mess, or, your brother never kicks the ball into the long grass, and you never seem to finish what you start.\n\nMany parents promise themselves, before they even marry, that they will never compare their kids. Then they end up doing exactly that.\n\nHow do you break the habit. Be deliberate. Talk to each child on their own without dragging the siblings into the picture. Instead of measuring one child against another, focus on what you see in this child alone. Describe what they did, what you like about it, what you do not like, or what still needs to be done. Stay with that child's behavior. What their siblings are up to is not part of the conversation. For example, instead of saying, this is awful, even your younger brother does not spill all over himself, you can simply say, I see a little milk dripping down your dress.\n\nA home that rewards cooperation helps kids function well, speak up for themselves, and reach the goals that matter to them.\n\nSometimes one child shares a small win in front of the others. How do you cheer them on without hurting the rest. Reflect their feelings back in front of everyone, and save the bigger praise for a private moment. If a child brings you a drawing while the siblings watch, say something like, wow, you must be so proud of yourself, rather than, I am thrilled, this is the best painting ever, I cannot wait to show everyone.\n\nFor context, a 2021 survey of two thousand adults, run for the UK television show Succession, found that 51 percent of those polled were still locked in a competitive relationship with their siblings."
      },
      {
        title: 'Equality vs. Unique attitude',
        text: "Children are not mature enough to want true fairness, even though they often ask for it, and many parents fall into the trap. At Faber and Mazlish's sibling rivalry workshop, parents often describe how hard it is to keep things even between their kids.\n\nOne mother told a story about a fairy tale she read to her two children, Billy and Roy. Both loved the story, but Roy started sobbing afterward, since the tale was all about Bill. She promised to track down a version with Roy in it, yet Roy would not stop crying. The challenge was clear. How can a parent read a fairy tale without leaving one child feeling left out.\n\nWhen your child asks who you love more, tell them they are each special because they are different.\n\nKids act like they want equal treatment, but the truth is that they do not. So instead of giving your children the same amount of food, drink, or attention, give them what each one needs. Showing them they are loved for who they are, not for being equal, teaches them how to handle the uneven parts of life.\n\nFor children, love is not about the exact amount of time or affection. It is about feeling like they matter as themselves. For example, do not say, you can have as many pancakes as your brother. Instead, ask, do you want a half pancake or a whole one. Rather than trying to spread love evenly with a line like, I love you both just the same, show them a unique kind of love. You can say, dear, you are such a special person. There is no other you in the universe, and I love you.\n\nAdele Faber and Elaine Mazlish have said that to be loved for who you are is to be loved as much as anyone needs to be loved.\n\nMake sure each of your kids feels like your favorite by respecting and responding to their differences."
      },
      {
        title: 'Even positive roles can be damaging',
        text: "One of the authors was out in the driveway with her dog one evening. The neighbor's kids came running up with their mother close behind, shouting doggy, doggy as they approached. The author was glad both children liked dogs. The mother then said the younger one was bold enough to play with the dog, while the older one liked dogs but stayed back. She went on, complaining that the kids had been this way since birth, calling the younger one bold and the older one shy. She did not see that she was putting her kids into boxes and quietly building resentment between them.\n\nSaying negative things about your children in front of them lowers their self-esteem and shapes how they handle relationships later in life.\n\nLocking kids into roles can hurt them on their own and in how they get along with others, and it is one of the main reasons siblings fight. A few things drive parents to assign roles, including the urge to project their own weak spots onto their kids, the bad habit of building one child up by putting the other down, and the comfort of believing they have each child fully figured out.\n\nParents are not the only ones who do this. Kids put themselves into boxes too. A child may take on the role of the good boy to win a parent's love. Kids also push each other into roles. A woman at the workshop said her small, skinny older son bragged about his strength and called his younger brother weak. The younger son, who was actually well-built, took the comments to heart and started acting that way. When anyone asked him to lift something heavy, he would say he could not, since it was too much. He had no real sense of his own strength, and that false belief would be hard to undo if the teasing kept up.\n\nDo not lock your kids into roles. To raise strong individuals, encourage them to explore who they are, test their strengths, and reach goals they did not know they could."
      },
      {
        title: 'What to do when kids fight',
        text: "Children fight for all kinds of reasons. They fight over toys, they fight because they are bored, and some just want to see how their parents will react. The best move when your kids quarrel is to stay out of it and let them work it out. The more you step in, the more they pull you in, and the less they learn to settle things on their own. Still, you should step in when they are in danger. Start by describing what you see, and then separate them.\n\nDo not try to settle your kids' fights. Help them get past the communication block so they can find their own answers.\n\nHere are a few ways to handle their quarrels. Acknowledge their anger toward each other. Give each child your full attention and listen well. Show you appreciate the moment without mocking their age. Tell them you know they are smart enough to find a fair solution. Then leave them alone to keep talking.\n\nSometimes, kids are upset about how a sibling treats them but cannot bring themselves to tell a parent. Most say their parents will not listen or think they are being dramatic. It is worth getting past that first reaction and helping them work things out.\n\nIn that case, start by meeting with the children who are having trouble and explain why you called them in. Let the child with the problem speak first without interruption, then let the other child give their side. As each child shares, write it down and read it back so they know you got it right. Then give each child a chance to respond, and let everyone suggest ways to fix the problem. Let the kids speak first, and write down all their ideas without judging them. Pick the solutions that everyone can live with, and set a follow-up meeting to see how things are going."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Sibling relationships shift in ways you cannot fully predict. Sisters and brothers may start with a hostile attitude and grow closer later in life. They may also drift apart as they move away from their parents.\n\nParents cannot force a fixed, close, loving bond between their children. The best they can do is gently clear the barriers that might stop their kids from building a deeper connection when the time is right.\n\nTry this. Ask your kids to write down things they admire about their siblings. Set up a calm family meeting to talk about family concerns, where each person's view is welcome and respected. Plan personal one-on-one time with each child so they get your full attention."
      }
    ]
  },

  'silent-spring.json': {
    base: { id: 'silent-spring', title: 'Silent Spring', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781683088536 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A message from Olga Huckins',
        text: "In January 1958, Olga Owens Huckins, a friend of Rachel Carson, wrote her a letter. Huckins was living in Massachusetts, where the state government was working hard to control the mosquito population. Their main tool was a mix of DDT, a pesticide, and fuel oil. The plan called for spraying certain areas with this mix, and Huckins' home was in the spray zone.\n\nAt the time, DDT makers and government officials told the public the pesticide was safe, and many campaigns pushed that message. But the morning after Huckins' neighborhood was sprayed, she found several of her favorite birds lying dead in her yard. The spraying had not wiped out the mosquitoes. In the long run, it had made the problem worse.\n\nWhen Carson began speaking out to rally the public against DDT and other harmful pesticides, pushback from the chemical industry was expected. Carson was not shaken. The message of Silent Spring reached President Kennedy, who set up a board of inquiry. The President's Panel later reported back and confirmed that Carson's claims about the harm done by chemical pesticides were sound.\n\nIt takes a single individual to start a revolution.\n\nCarson brought the science of ecology to the average American's door, and people began to grasp the danger. Pressure from the public pushed government at all levels to look at environmental laws.\n\nThis summary will make you aware of a quiet kind of poisoning, the kind that happens when chemicals are spread across the land. You will also see how human activity is putting the balance of nature under strain. Read it through to learn how you can help bring back that balance."
      },
      {
        title: 'The abstractions of life make us humble to death',
        text: "The whole story of life on Earth has always involved the way living things interact with their environment. The plants and animals alive today have been shaped by the world they live in. Given the age of the Earth and the activities of the past few centuries, a new normal has set in. One species, humans, has built up enough intelligence and power to flip the old order. Nature is now at the mercy of human activity, and the effects are sharper than ever.\n\nThe threat to people and to nature at large is starting to come into focus.\n\nDroughts, tsunamis, floods, landslides, and climate change are all signs that the Earth is under stress. Some experts see these problems but do not think through what they mean in the bigger picture. Business, production, and trade now run on a massive industrial scale. The goal is often to make another dollar, whatever the cost to nature. Few people worry about the heat given off by bitcoin mining server farms, as long as the money keeps coming.\n\nIt is time for the human race to step up, push aside the false promises, and stop accepting the claims of the clever and the unverified. The public of the twentieth century paid the price when insect control efforts failed. The job now belongs to ordinary people, armed with the truth about what our inventions really do, to decide what to accept and what to reject.\n\nJean Rostand once said that the duty to endure gives us the right to know.\n\nEvery living person is exposed to dangerous chemicals, from the first breath to the last. That exposure is the result of a sudden boom in industries making synthetic chemicals that kill insects."
      },
      {
        title: 'Understanding the interconnectedness of the earth\'s waters, soil, animals, and greenery',
        text: "The danger of widespread contamination in the water people use is not only the toxicity but the cancer risk. Authorities can barely control the leak of some of these harmful substances into public water supplies. Dr. W. C. Hueper of the National Cancer Institute warned that the cancer risk from drinking polluted water would rise sharply in the years to come, and that future is already here.\n\nWater pollution is a complex issue and a part of the environmental strain caused by industry.\n\nThe soil is the next victim of human contamination. The thin crust of soil that covers the land over Earth's waters and continents shapes the life of every land animal. Without this soil, plants and animals cannot thrive, and the loss of plants brings harm to animals, directly or indirectly.\n\nWith the steady use of pesticides, hard-to-break-down residues pile up in the soil around the world. Some of these substances are broken down into less harmful forms by natural processes in the soil, but the buildup is faster than the breakdown. In 1960, experts met at Syracuse University to study soil health. They warned that if humans misuse strong tools like chemicals and radiation, the soil would be harmed, and arthropods would take over.\n\nThe plant life on the planet is part of a living network that shows the close and crucial partnership between the Earth and its plants. Sometimes that partnership has to be disturbed, but honesty demands that we think carefully about what our actions mean in time and place."
      },
      {
        title: 'Humans are self-hypnotic; they wage wars against nature and scar the planet Earth',
        text: "There is a real hurdle for anyone who tries to judge the loss of wildlife from chemical pesticides. Experts say the losses have been severe, and in some places catastrophic. Regulatory bodies, on the other hand, deny or downplay the harm, calling it small or unimportant.\n\nMost pesticides are not selective. They cannot be aimed at one species. They are used because they are deadly. They poison every form of life they touch, from a pet cat to a rabbit in the field, from farm cattle to the horned lark in the sky.\n\nIn 1954, the year light spraying of pesticides began in the U.S., things at first looked normal. The next spring, Professor George Wallace, an ornithologist at Michigan State University, and one of his graduate students watched the yearly return of robins to the campus. The birds settled back into their usual spots without knowing what had changed. Soon, red flags appeared. Dead and dying robins turned up all over the campus. Their normal feeding habits shifted, and so did their roosting patterns. Far fewer nests were found than the year before, and very few young robins appeared. The pattern kept repeating every spring after that.\n\nBirds have been shown by many studies to play a key role in keeping insects in check.\n\nFor every robin that came back to the MSU campus, the sprayed area acted like a deadly trap and killed the bird within a week.\n\nFisheries are a vital resource that affects the wellbeing of many people. Aquatic animals cannot walk away from their habitat, and that habitat is slowly becoming the cause of their decline. The serious threat from chemicals getting into waterways can no longer be ignored.\n\nIf we put even a small part of the money we spend on stronger pesticides into useful research, we would be in a much better position to use safer materials and keep poisons out of the ecosystem."
      },
      {
        title: 'Aiming at the duck and killing the child',
        text: "The market for toxic and poisonous substances is so well established that anyone with money can walk into a store and buy one. A short look at the shelves in any average supermarket shows how many products with harmful base ingredients are up for sale. Some of these substances are more dangerous than hard drugs.\n\nFor example, many moth-proofing products have labels in tiny print warning that the can is under pressure and can explode near heat or flame. A compound often found in homes, especially kitchens, is chlordane. Even though a top official at the Food and Drug Administration pointed out the serious risk of living in a chlordane-sprayed house, these products are still on the market. Some household items contain even more harmful compounds, such as dieldrin.\n\nThe hazards of gardening with chemical products or using cleaning sprays at home are also part of the picture. The warning labels are so small that they are easy to miss. Herbicides are sold under brand names that say nothing about their ingredients or what they actually do. Figuring out if a product contains chlordane or dieldrin takes careful reading of the fine print, often hidden on the least visible side of the package.\n\nEach repeated exposure to a hazardous chemical adds to the body's total toxic load.\n\nThe packaging for some risky products sold in garden or hardware stores rarely mentions the dangers. The pictures on the box show a happy family scene, like a mother gardening with her daughter while they apply the chemicals to vegetables, windowsills, or even the living room. In some ads, small children are shown tumbling on the grass with a dog.\n\nFor context, body fat, which makes up about 18 percent of body weight, has many important functions that can be disrupted by the buildup of drugs and chemicals."
      },
      {
        title: 'The microscopic view and nature\'s affront',
        text: "The way natural chemicals work inside cells, when properly understood, is one of the wonders of the living world. All the parts involved in these processes are tiny, which makes the whole system feel like a grand miracle.\n\nWe cannot ignore what it means to flood the environment with chemicals that can damage key parts of our cells, like chromosomes. Since chromosomes shape the identity of a cell and the organism it belongs to, breaking them is a heavy price to pay for saving potatoes or wiping out mosquitoes in the yard. With a real commitment to protecting our genetic heritage, we can lower this risk if we choose to.\n\nOur genes are a temporary loan from our ancestors, meant to be passed on to the next generation.\n\nIn 1775, Sir Percivall Pott, a British surgeon, noticed a possible link between the soot-covered bodies of chimney sweeps and the high rate of scrotal cancer among them. He could not prove it at the time, but later research confirmed the harmful chemical in soot, supporting Pott's theory.\n\nHere is how the Pott discovery applies to us. Pesticides used to control nature can cause cancer. Animal tests show that five or six of the most common pesticides are carcinogenic. Around the same period, when modern and improved pesticides came into wide use, the rate of leukemia began to climb steadily.\n\nNature has refused to sit still. Studies done after the heavy spraying of the twentieth century show a large jump in the population of the very insects the spraying was meant to control. In Ontario, for example, the number of blackflies grew seventeen times after spraying. In another case, England had a huge outbreak of the cabbage aphid, a scale of attack with no equal in history, after organic phosphorus chemicals were sprayed.\n\nNature adapts and fights back."
      },
      {
        title: 'The necessity of charting a new course — the sign',
        text: "If Charles Darwin were alive today, he would have been amazed and delighted by the insects and other living things around the world. His excitement would come from how clearly his ideas about the survival of the fittest were being proven. Under the sudden shock of heavy chemical spraying, the weaker members of a species die off first, since they cannot adapt quickly.\n\nIn many parts of the world, only the toughest and most resilient members of each species are still here, in spite of our efforts to control them.\n\nDr. Briejèr, who headed the Plant Protection Service in Holland, argued that accepting a little damage now is wiser than putting it off and suffering a much larger loss later. The smart path is to keep chemical spraying to the barest minimum, rather than going all out with the products on hand. Dr. Briejèr's point is that pressure on the pest population should be kept as light as possible.\n\nThe deck of cards sits on the table, and it is up to us to decide how to play them. Life on Earth has put up with a great deal of chemical pollution, but humans now know better. We are aware of the frightening risks of our destructive activity. We can no longer accept the advice of those who want to soak our fragile ecosystem in poisonous chemicals. We have to weigh the tradeoffs and look at other practical options."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "During her time working for the government, Rachel Carson and her scientific colleagues could not stay quiet after they saw the alarming biological effects of widespread DDT use and other long-lasting poisons in so-called agricultural control programs.\n\nSoon after the war, when the dangers were already well known, Carson tried to get magazines to publish pieces that would educate the public. Progress was slow, and the damage done by toxic pesticides and herbicides to wildlife and humans kept piling up. She took action, and her work paid off. Even though the companies making huge profits from these products attacked her reputation and rejected most of her work, the public ended up better informed about the problem.\n\nThe Earth's ecosystem faces many challenges, including the need for living things to share space and resources. Our decisions affect many lives, especially as the human population grows. We have to guide these factors carefully, in our favor. Until we do, we will not make peace with the insects around us.\n\nTry this. The state of the Earth today is the result of the actions of people who lived before you. What will you do to leave a habitable planet for your children? If you are not sure where to start, first look at the parts of your life that add to environmental damage. Then decide which of those you can fix. Finally, take real steps to make up for the harm you can correct."
      }
    ]
  },

  'sleep-smarter.json': {
    base: { id: 'sleep-smarter', title: 'Sleep Smarter', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781683192373 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Your sleep rocks',
        text: "Think back to the last morning you swung your legs out of bed with a grin. How often do you find yourself fighting yawns by your third cup of coffee, or wrestling with insomnia while your mind loops over old mistakes. If any of that fits, it is time to learn more about sleep.\n\nKnowledge is not just a weapon. It is also a foundation for happiness.\n\nIt is common to trade hours of rest for work, but the price is steep. Sleep turns on dozens of body processes that repair and improve you, including the release of hormones. These chemicals shape how organs and tissues function, and they also shape how you feel. For instance, dreaming lifts serotonin, the pleasure hormone, and lowers cortisol, the stress hormone. Sleep also makes you sharper because the brain sorts through your day and turns it into long-term memory. Every neuron and cell does its part to help you feel ready in the morning.\n\nDo you want to thank those tireless workers and become a better manager of your rest. Then dive into this summary for clear answers about sleep and simple tools to lift its quality."
      },
      {
        title: 'Enhancing your sleep through habits',
        text: "No matter how complex the chemistry of sleep may seem, it all rests on simple basics. You can go through your day without realizing that small choices are already shaping your rest. Take curtains, for example. Are yours thick enough? Your body senses light through your skin as well as your eyes, so even a sleep mask may not block every ray. Make the bedroom as dark as possible, and you will fall asleep faster.\n\nGood rest is the key to good work.\n\nFor many people, the only bright spot in the morning is coffee. It is a beloved drink that has become part of daily life for millions. There is nothing wrong with coffee or other pick-me-ups in moderation, but the dose matters. Caffeine does not give you energy. It only stimulates the nervous system, and once the effect fades, you feel even more tired.\n\nCaffeine also has a long half-life, so it stays in your body for hours. A large cup in the morning can still affect your sleep at night. Giving up an old habit is tough, but try to skip caffeine in the afternoon. A mild tea or a glass of water can help you handle stress just as well.\n\nMany people hold a coffee in one hand and a smartphone in the other. The phone is a useful tool, and it has become a normal part of life. Still, putting both down before bed can do a lot for your rest. The intense blue light from screens strains the eyes and wakes up the brain when it should be winding down.\n\nElectronic devices also give off waves that can disturb sleep. Studies show that people who use gadgets before bed tend to scroll for a long time, sleep later, and get poorer rest than people who do other things. Try reading a paper book, playing with your pet, or talking with your partner before bed. Your dreams may be a lot nicer after that."
      },
      {
        title: 'In rhythm with your sleep',
        text: "Everything in nature runs on quiet rules, and our bodies are no different. Our biology follows a circadian rhythm, which shifts across the day. Our ancestors matched their lives to the sun, waking at sunrise and sleeping at sunset. That pattern kept them active during the safer daylight hours, since the night was risky.\n\nModern technology has pushed the body's natural cycle, letting people work well past midnight. Compared to thousands of years of natural sleep, a few decades of late-night living is short. Some needs have not changed, though, like getting about eight hours of sleep each night.\n\nThat number is not a random guess. Sleep moves in cycles of roughly ninety minutes, split into two main phases. Light sleep, also called REM, comes with rapid eye movement. The second phase is deep sleep without eye movement, which is when you get the most energy, though waking up from it can feel rough. It is better to set your alarm for the end of a REM phase, when you are dreaming. After about five cycles, around eight hours, you will wake up feeling clear.\n\nThe quality of sleep matters as much as the amount. The body makes the right amount of key hormones between 10 pm and 2 am. Melatonin, which helps with growth and repair, is produced heavily in that window, which is why many people get a second wind late at night and want to get things done. That may sound like a good idea, but if you want to save on anti-wrinkle cream, rest is the better choice.\n\nEveryone has a unique system, so it helps to pay attention to how you react, even in everyday life.\n\nSleep habits have become a part of pop culture. You may have heard the split between night owls, who struggle to get up early but work hard late, and early birds, who wake up easily but slow down in the afternoon. In most offices, early birds find it easier to fit the standard schedule. Owls, on the other hand, are often seen as more creative. Understanding your body and balancing your rhythm with your work is important, no matter which side you lean toward. That way, you can plan your day better and stay productive."
      },
      {
        title: 'Satisfaction, sex, and sleep: the three "s" that make each other better',
        text: "Beyond work and productivity, there is the romantic side of life. Sex, sleep, and satisfaction support each other in a strong way. When you sleep next to a partner while massaging, hugging, or touching skin, the body releases oxytocin, a hormone that helps with stress, lowers the chance of depression, and helps control blood pressure.\n\nProlactin, which is released during sex, also rises during sleep. A good intimate experience can improve a relationship and make it easier to rest well afterward.\n\nThe link works both ways. Not only does sex affect sleep, but the reverse is true too. Poor rest leads to weakness and a lower sex drive, and it raises the risk of intimate health problems. Medical research has shown that sexual activity goes up by about 14 percent after a good night's rest. Want better closeness with your partner. Make sure you both sleep well first.\n\nTo build a calm setting, the bedroom should feel like a place for rest and pleasure. A few ideas may help. Do not bring a laptop or work to bed. Let the bedroom be a place for rest, not for tasks. If you have been working there all day, you will struggle to drop the thoughts of upcoming projects in the evening.\n\nAdd a few small items that you like to the bedroom. Small details shape the mood. Invite your partner to help design the space together. It can be a fun way to feel closer.\n\nYou can show warmth and care at any moment in life.\n\nEven without sex, evening talks or sharing a bed can be a strong way to grow closer, or a reason to argue. Everyone has their own sleeping habits, so talk with your partner and find compromises. Do you need one blanket or two. Which pillows work best. Maybe one of you has a strong preference.\n\nShawn Stevenson has said that your choices affect you so much more because you are so much more.\n\nCare and respect matter in this talk. As you make key decisions together, you will grow closer and lift each other's lives. Is that not worth the effort."
      },
      {
        title: 'You sleep the way you eat',
        text: "Even the tiniest cells in your body are linked to millions of other cells, and they talk to each other faster than you message your friends. So when you eat something your stomach does not like, your brain gets a fast signal through the nervous system. The body reacts, and the result can be a restless night. What happens when you do not get enough sleep? You may overeat or lose your appetite. The good news is that the link works both ways. Just as poor food choices hurt you, good nutrition can lift your health.\n\nTake care of your body, and your body will take care of you.\n\nFirst, check whether you are getting enough vitamins. One of the key minerals for good sleep is magnesium. Scientists say up to 80 percent of people in the U.S. do not get enough of it, and that gap is linked to poor sleep and even to a higher risk of early death.\n\nYou can find magnesium in seafood, whole grains, vegetables, plant extracts, salts, and oils. That is good news for the bacteria in your stomach, which will start lifting the body's health right away. Still, try to finish eating at least an hour and a half before bed. Digestion uses resources and raises the body's internal activity, which is not great for sleep.\n\nGood food goes well with movement. Do you have a favorite workout? Exercise can help you lose weight, and extra weight is often behind sleep problems. During exercise, body temperature rises because of stress hormones and then drops over the next four to six hours. If you work out around 4 pm, your temperature will drop and you will relax by 10 pm, which is the best window for sleep. An athlete who trains hard but does not sleep well will not see the results they want. The body releases the chemicals that build muscle and break down fat at night.\n\nShort on time for long gym sessions? Yoga or quiet walks at lunch also help. Doing these things outside gives you sunlight, which your body needs to make melatonin. By the end of the day, that stored melatonin will make it easier to fall asleep."
      },
      {
        title: 'Small recipes for big sleep',
        text: "Your bedroom is a haven. You should feel at ease there, especially in bed. The mattress has to support your frame. It should be neither too firm nor too soft, so you can lie in a healthy line.\n\nWhat is the best position to sleep in. Many recommend back sleeping because airflow through the body is good in that position, though it can make breathing harder for some people. Stomach sleeping may make breathing easier, but it can put the spine in a bad place.\n\nA lot of people sleep on their side, which echoes the position we held before birth. The embryo curls that way, and adults return to the same shape to feel safe and breathe easily. Side sleeping can lead to poorer blood flow in the arms and legs, though.\n\nNo matter which style you favor, you can lift the experience with a pillow of the right height and softness.\n\nStill struggling to drift off. Try a few of these ideas. Run an ionizer or a humidifier in the room. Sleep in a cool room under a warm blanket rather than sweating. Aim for a temperature between 60 and 68 degrees Fahrenheit. Take a warm bath before bed to help your body temperature ease down.\n\nNo luck. Then it may be time to deal with the chatter in your head.\n\nPeople do not give themselves enough time alone, so they rarely notice the worries that drive them.\n\nAt rest, the brain replays everything that weighs on you. The bedroom should feel free of fear. To quiet intrusive thoughts, give meditation a try.\n\nShawn Stevenson has said that our ability to focus and finish what we start is a big part of overall success.\n\nMeditation does not have to be tied to a religion. It can be as simple as a quiet walk, counting steps, or giving full attention to a task like washing dishes. It may feel hard at first, but even short sessions will help you lower stress, find calm, and understand your feelings better. Just as exercise matters for the body, meditation matters for the mind.\n\nFor context, research from the National Institutes of Health shows that people spend about a third of their lives sleeping, which works out to roughly twenty-six years on average."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Sleep is your quiet corner, your retreat, and a pleasure only you can truly appreciate. Every part of life depends on it, and none of those parts work well without rest. These days, with new technology that lets us trade rest for work, getting a good night is harder than ever. Trading sleep for work only leads to trouble.\n\nMaking good sleep a priority can turn your days into something special. Fulfillment feeds happiness, and sleep is the best way to reach it.\n\nTry this. Take in more daylight. It triggers many helpful hormones. Use a classic alarm clock by your bed, not your phone, so you are not tempted to stay up late on a screen. Pick comfortable pajamas. Changing clothes in the evening signals that it is time to rest."
      }
    ]
  }
};
